"Deadline" was a short work of science fiction published to Astounding Stories in the year 1944. Its premise surrounded the separation of radioactive isotopes, namely uranium-235, to create a nuclear fission device. The story was published at around the same time the Manhattan Project was underway, and prompted an investigation by the FBI into its author's— Cleve Cartmill's— knowledge of the weapon.1 Allegedly, Cartmill was already aware that the United States government was constructing an atomic weapon. He apparently cited that subscribers to the Astounding Stories magazine, many of whom were physicists and engineers, had all suddenly changed their addresses to Los Alamos, New Mexico.

What is known for certain, however, is that the editor of Astounding Stories at the time, John Campbell, is recorded to have corresponded with Cartmill on the subject of a so-called "super-bomb.” He mentioned the concept of using atomic weaponry in warfare, directing him to scientific articles describing a process whereby fissionable uranium-235 can be generated. [2]

[2]: https://www.gwern.net/docs/1984-berger.pdf Refer to page 8 of the PDF, corresponding to p.132

The FBI’s investigation also led them to H. G. Wells and Robert A. Heinlein, both are well known science fiction authors today. It is worth noting that H. G. Wells, though he is better known for novels like War of the Worlds and The Time Machine, also wrote a novel depicting the use of nuclear weaponry— though of a slightly different form— titled The World Set Free.

This anecdote begs the question: what can the trends of science fiction reveal about history? The history of science fiction in itself is already well-tread ground, but even a cursory knowledge of the genre hints toward a deeper relationship between itself and developments in conventional science. One of the agreed-upon founders of science fiction, Mary Shelley, was openly inspired by research into “animal electricity” to create the premise of Frankenstein. In a more topical vein, there is a clear trend in the depiction of nuclear radiation following Hiroshima and Nagasaki, one that notably differs between the United States and Japan.

The common approach to the history of science fiction is often focused upon a few authors and their contributions to the genre. There are the well-known and agreed-upon founders, Mary Shelley and some of the "fathers of science fiction," H. G. Wells, Jules Vernes, Isaac Asimov, et cetera. There is alway the occasional detour, mentioning the likes of H. P. Lovecraft or Frank Herbert, who both revolutionised the genre in their own ways. While this approach is good, it inevitably constrains itself to popular or singular works, which might not be totally representative of the entire genre at that time. Additionally, while innovative writers have had extreme influence on the genre, such an approach may miss this influence upon lesser-known works of science fiction.

A possible solution is to take a more broad approach, using data-driven techniques to analyse science fiction as a whole. This approach is obviously missing the keen focus mentioned beforehand, but for what it lacks in popular authorship, it makes up in representation and zeitgeist. More eminently, however, the upcoming techniques and analyses may be used at a much larger scale to analyse any body of work, not simply science fiction. What follows is a methodological exploration. The intention is to investigate the relationship between conventional science and science fiction, much in the way the introductory anecdote suggests.

It would help to first define what it means for a work to be “science fiction” in the first place. Generally, a narrative is called “science fiction” either when its premise cannot exist without the inclusion some scientific concept or when its plot centres around a certain technology. Strangely enough, by this definition, certain works cannot strictly be called “science fiction,” most notably Star Wars, in which every idea can be traded for a corresponding idea of traditional fantasy. For the purpose of upcoming analyses, however, “science fiction” may as well be defined narrowly, as “anything which has been published to a pulp magazine popular after 1920s." The general definition is only present to create a connection between science fiction narrative and the history of conventional science.

And to represent conventional science, data will be pulled from Nature, one of the largest and broadest scientific journals in history. Nature publishes articles covering a wide variety of subjects, including, but not limited to: biology, physics, chemistry, psychology, metaanalyses, commentary, et cetera. As implied by the Amazing Stories dataset, the Nature dataset will only cover English language articles.

It is worth mentioning the potential for loss in the datasets, as the accrual of both met certain drawbacks and limitations. The chosen reference index of Amazing Stories does not contain permanent archives for every single issue, thereby incurring some loss. The chosen method for gathering Nature articles is unable to guarantee there is an abstract for all entries; additionally, a combination of the sheer abundance of data, user impatience, and poor internet connection forced the dataset to be culled by way of skipping entries. Each instance of loss will be elaborated upon when relevant.

When allowed to execute until the end of the available dataset— though not recommended— the Python cell below has a runtime of eight minutes and forty-seven seconds, and it yields 183 plaintext files into the user's default directory. These files will act as the dataset for the holistic analysis of science fiction. A folder containing all 183 documents will be provided alongside this Python notebook.

As there were many pulp magazines that specialised in science fiction, the dataset has been limited to the most easily accessible one on the internet: Amazing Stories. The script below is designed to scrape the internet for as many full text issues of the Amazing Stories periodical as possible, a set which just so happens to fall between the 1920s and the 1950s. There will not be an explanation for every single line; the lines deemed the most important will take priority.

The source for this analysis is the Online Books Page, a reference index containing links to permanent physical or digital archives for works of literature. In particular, the script is designed to scrape the page containing every available archive of Amazing Stories, all thankfully digital, and pull plaintext files into the user's directory.

The reference index contains links to three different online archives, those being HathiTrust, the Gutenberg Project, and the Internet Archive. A majority of the indeces come from the Internet Archive, so to save time, the lines above filter for only the links that go to archive.org, the Internet Archive's web domain.

"""
SCRIPT #1
"""
## necessary imports
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

site = requests.get("https://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/webbin/serial?id=amazingstories").text
soupsite = BeautifulSoup(site, "lxml")

references = soupsite.find("ul") # yields the 'unordered list' HTML element containing each reference link 
references_links = references.find_all("a") # yields a list of HTML elements

archive_links = [i.get("href") for i in references_links if "archive.org" in i.get("href")] ## yields a list of direct links to archive.org archives
archive_titles = [i.text for i in references_links if "archive.org" in i.get("href")] ## yields volume and issue number

print(archive_titles)

good_links = [] ## empty list which by the end of the following loop should contain every necessary link
for link in archive_links:
    try:
        archive = requests.get(link).text
        souparchive = BeautifulSoup(archive, "lxml")
        
        sidebar_div = souparchive.find("div", class_="col-sm-4 thats-right item-details-archive-info")
        a_tags = sidebar_div.find_all("a")
        
        text_links = [i.get("href") for i in a_tags if "FULL TEXT" in i.text]
        
        good_links = good_links + text_links
        
        print(text_links)
    except:
        pass

for link in good_links:
    plaintext = requests.get(f"https://archive.org{link}").text ## link to a web archive which contains the plaintext inside a unique HTML tag
    soupplaintext = BeautifulSoup(plaintext, "lxml")
    
    best = soupplaintext.find("pre").text ## yields a string
    
    with open(f"{archive_titles[good_links.index(link)]}.txt", "w") as f:
        f.write(best)

By the variable names, it should be clear what is occurring inside this loop: for each iteration, the code will enter an archive.org link and locate the <div> element that represents a sidebar in the actual webpage. Within the sidebar, there is another link, labelled "FULL TEXT", that goes to the desired plaintext file, stored inside an HTML webpage withing a <pre> tag.

The line labelled "## EXAMPLE" is an important factor in both hastening the analysis of the data and cleaning the data itself. The variable is formed using a unique tool of Python, called "list comprehension," which is a single line script that runs within the variable itself. Each term of the self-contained function has a particular use.

The first instance of 'i' in the function defines the data which will be saved to the list. The subsequent loop, 'for i in token_book if in shortlist' constrains or filters the list to a particular set of words. In this case, it is the 'shortlist' variable defined at the beginning of the script. This method of cleaning data appears extremely destructive, since every word in the dataset is lost except those that match the 'shortlist' variable. This is not truly the case, mercifully, since 'rep_book' is generated using a read-only process, which does not affect the original text file whatsoever.

The benefit of this cleaning is a significantly more efficient runtime. For example, Volume 1 Issue 1 of Amazing Stories, when extracted via the previous script, contains 117,639 words according to the returned list from Natural Language Toolkit's word_tokenize() method. After cleaning, the list contains only 624 words, a difference of three orders of magnitude and an astronomical burden lifted from the script's time complexity.

Note the empty comment syntax surrounding the last few lines. Were everything between the two octothorps to be indented to line up with the for-loop, the csv_writer line above would run once for every document, and after runtime yield a complete CSV with data for all 183 documents.

Said CSV has hopefully been included with this notebook file under the name 'amazingstories.csv'.

In its current state, the script above is of little use. However, the technique of removing every unnecessary word will be eminent for upcoming analyses and data visualisations. The technique is especially effective in the case of the plaintext files generated in Script #1. If the user were to have opened any of the files extracted by S1, they would find that each contains a few lines of garbled text at the beginning. By first tokenising and then cleaning the files in a read-only manner, S2 demonstrates an efficient method for analysing only the frequency of highly relevant words. Articles, demonstratives, pronouns, and prepositions— which would normally be cleaned out as "stopwords"— are all automatically excluded during list comprehension. In this way, it is nearly possible to select any word and learn its frequency through the years of Amazing Stories. To get there, however, the script still needs work.

Two problems are immediately apparent. The first is obvious: there are no dates recorded. The second is slightly more abstract. Consider the following example to illustrate the problem:

The user wants to analyse the frequency of the word "dog" in a pair of files individually. They input the word and execute the script, and they are met with two values: File #1 contains 10 instances of the word, whereas File #2 contains 100. The user is left to conclude that "dog" has more significance in file two than File #1. Their conclusion, however, is not guaranteed to be accurate; F1 may contain exactly 10 words, inducing a 100% significance on the word "dog," likewise F2 may contain 100,000 words, inducing only a 0.1% significance. Correcting this discrepancy involves normalising the data, that is: dividing word frequency by the total number of words in the parent document. This process shrinks every value to the same relative size, preserving their relationships to one another in a manner that ensures direct comparability.

"""
SCRIPT #4
"""
## necessary imports
import os
import nltk

from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
from natsort import natsorted

## defined function
def wordfreq(word, factor):
        p = 0
        
        dir_list = os.listdir()
        txt_files = [i for i in dir_list if i.endswith(".txt")]
        txt_files = natsorted(txt_files)
        
        statistics = {}
        
        for file in txt_files:
            
            book = open(file, "r")
            book = book.read()
            book = book.lower()
            
            token_book = nltk.word_tokenize(book)
            rep_book = [i for i in token_book if i in word]

            total = len(token_book)
            rep = len(rep_book)
            
            normal = (rep/total) * factor
            """
            The inclusion of a 'factor' variable allows for the normalised data to be represented as positive real numbers of arbitrary size. Provided all normalised datapoints are multiplied by the same 'factor', comparability is preserved. The proof for this is simple and requires only an understanding of arithmetic (the use of "we" is a commonplace formality in mathematical proofs, similar to the term "the user" employed thusfar):
            
            PROOF:
            Suppose we are given a pair of real-valued absolute frequencies and we wish to compare them. First, we normalise the values by dividing the absolute frequencies by the total word-lengths of their parent documents, yielding a pair of relative frequencies represented as percentages.
            
            Let these relative frequencies take the form x/100 and y/100. Since x, y, and 100 are all real numbers per the previous lines, both x/100 and y/100 are also real numbers.
            
            This is true by group theory; to put it briefly, all well-defined operations on the real numbers— like addition or multiplication— must yield a real number (hauntingly enough, the square root operation is not well-defined on all real numbers).
            
            Let the relation between x/100 and y/100 be '~'. By an axiom on the real numbers, this relation may be exactly one of '=', '<', or '>'. 
            
            Suppose we would like to have values which are easier to work with. We might want to multiply the relative frequencies by some common factor.
            
            Given x/100 ~ y/100, we multiply both sides by some factor A, yielding Ax/100 ~ Ay/100. The relation '~' is preserved by another axiom of the real numbers, that for any of the relations '=', '<', or '>', x ~ y if and only if xz ~ yz.
            
            The above is true for arbitrarily many relative frequencies, provided they are all multiplied by the same factor.
            ◻︎
            """
            
            ## key and value pair for dictionary element introduced at the beginning of the script
            statistics[file] = normal
            
            p += 1
        
        return statistics

Below is a manifestly frustrating script saddled with the ambitious goal of scraping nature.com, the web domain of one of the longest running scientific journals in history. It is severely not recommended to run this script, as it will manifest a human form in front of the user and personally tear the life essence out of their body.

The script was written to scrape the journal search of nature.com between pages 7100 to 6000 for titles, dates, and abstracts, skipping five pages at a time. Those particular page numbers were chosen because they coincide with roughly the same time frame as the Amazing Stories corpus extracted by S1 (in mercifully less time).

Normalising datapoints is especially key when it comes to analysing the text outputs generated by this script, as word frequencies will be significantly inflated by their length. It is no surprise that Nature would contain more abundant and more robust data than the Internet Archive, so there is much less concern for loss. The page-skipping aspect of the script was implemented to save time, and may raise some concern, since there is a chance that highly representative abstracts for a given year are skipped over. This is considered to be offset by the likelihood that the script reduplicates an abstract, which occurs when the script throws its umpteenth ConnectionError meanwhile other internet services perform just fine, forcing the user to start over from the last page it attempted to scrape.

"""
SCRIPT #5
"""
## necessary imports
import requests

from bs4 import BeautifulSoup 
from datetime import datetime as dt

## main script
x = 6260
while x >= 6000:
    
    nature = requests.get(f"https://www.nature.com/nature/research-articles?searchType=journalSearch&sort=PubDate&page={x}").text
    soupnature = BeautifulSoup(nature, "lxml")
    
    nature_list = soupnature.find_all("article")
    
    ## main loop of the script, which handles gathering abstracts from each individual page
    for item in nature_list:
        nature_link = item.find("a").get("href")
        
        article = requests.get(f"https://www.nature.com{nature_link}").text
        souparticle = BeautifulSoup(article, "lxml")
        
        nature_article = souparticle.find("article")
        
        article_title = nature_article.find("h1").text
        article_date = nature_article.find("time").text
        try:
            article_abstract = nature_article.find("div", id="Abs1-content").find("p").text
        except:
            article_abstract = "n/a"
            
        article_year = dt.strptime(article_date, "%d %B %Y").year
        
        ## in theory, this should provide me with text files corresponding to each year of articles
        ## whenever the year changes, the filename changes, and so Python writes a new file to the default directory
        ## the "a" argument allows me to append text to the file directly
        with open(f"year_bias{article_year}.txt", "a") as f:
            if article_abstract != "n/a":
                f.write(f"{article_abstract} ")
        
        print(f"{article_title}\n{article_date}\n{article_abstract}\n{article_year}\n\n")
        print(x)
    
    print(x)
    x -= 5

print(x)

"""

The output of S9 is surprising, particularly with regards to the Nature dataset. The frequency of nuclear-related terminology appears to sharply decline between 1939 and 1947, when it returns to its regular rates. This dip in frequency follows a sequence of peaks, the largest being in 1934. Checking the corresponding plaintext file reveals that there indeed happens to be an abundance of nuclear-related terminology, and skimming through the collected abstracts that contain those terms reveals experimentation with unstable isotopes of various atoms, some indeed being uranium. If there is one fault in the test variable, it is that it did not initially include 'uranium'.

Looking further into the drop and corroborating with some outside information, the span between 1939 and 1947 overlaps the active period of the Manhattan Project— which ran from 1942 to 1946— completely. Investigating the dip reveals that there indeed was a period of censorship beginning in 1939, in which the number of American publications related to nuclear physics declined. This makes sense, considering the United States has consistently been a top three scientific publisher since 1900, [6] thus a decline American research to any subject reflects sharply in the data. In 1943, the Office of Censorship sent a notice to every newspaper and radio station in the United States, ordering them to refrain from publishing information about nuclear science. [7] This does not completely explain the small hump in 1943, though it does explain the continued absence of research until 1947.

[6]: https://direct.mit.edu/qss/article/3/1/37/109076/Scopus-1900-2020-Growth-in-articles-abstracts Refer to Figs. 7 and 8 especially when regarding American dominance in scientific publishing. Also note the sharp decline in both figs. for all nations' output corresponding with the 1940s.

[7]: https://archive.org/details/secretsofvictory00swee/page/200/mode/2up Borrow the book using a free account and refer to page 200.

Since the Amazing Stories data was dwarfed by Nature in the output for S9, S10 outputs the isolated relationships. Immediately the user can spot a sharp incline in the frequency of nuclear-related terminology during 1945 with an obvious culprit. Another set of peaks are reflected in 1932 and 1934, which either coincide with or directly follow peaks in Nature data, likely reflecting waxing and waning interest in nuclear concepts within science fiction.

Three peaks in the Nature data seem to inform the behaviour of the Amazing Stories data, an initial peak in 1927, one in 1932, and one in 1935. The 1927 peak appears to initiate an incline in the mentions of nuclear-related terminology in the Amazing Stories data, which comes to a summit in 1932, whereupon it experiences a brief drop. Since the frequency data is normalised, this drop does not correlate with the file sizes of the original plaintext, and investigating their sizes reveals that preceding and following files are actually smaller than the 1934 file. The peak in the 1927 Nature data appears to correspond with the development of the uncertainty principle by Werner Heisenberg, which forms a basis for many nuclear and quantum mechanical ideas. 8 This correlation is not easily confirmed, however.

Checking the file corresponding to the peak in 1932 reveals several short stories containing abundant mentions of terms like "nuclear," "radiation," and "atomic," which is expected. The first term is primarily found in a story titled "The Legend of Posi and Nega," a love story between a proton and an electron, though it gets mentioned elsewhere in a manner reflected more heavily in the latter two terms. "Radiation" and "atomic," in the stories published during 1934, seemed to be buzzwords closely related to power and electricity. Investigating what occured in 1932 to cause this reveals two historical events: February 27th, when James Chadwick published evidence of the neutron to Nature [9], and April 14th, when John Cockcroft and Ernest Walton first split the atom and found that it released energy consistent with Einstein's mass-energy equivalence. 10 It was the latter event that likely garnered more popularity and initiated discussion about nuclear energy.

[9]: This article was published to Nature, however S5 was unable to capture it, since it was skipping pages five at a time. https://www.nature.com/articles/129312a0

The 1935 peak incurs more of the same usage of "nuclear" and "atomic" as energy-related terms, with such gems as atomic converters, atomic generators, atomic homes, and atomic consciousness. "The Legend of Posi and Nega" makes a return, containing some of the stranger atomic concepts. All of this follows a peak in the Nature data in 1934. On February 10, 1934, an article was published to Nature describing the artificial production of radioactive elements. 11 This was followed by the work of Enrico Fermi to increase the effectiveness of that process. 12

If the user compares the frequency labels of the output of S12 to other outputs, they will find they show much less significance. However, there is an extremely notable peak in the Amazing Stories data in in 1939. Investigating all previous peaks in the Nature data reveals no correlation, and every abstract containing the words "freeze" and "freezing" pertains to some branch of chemistry. However, looking into the Amazing Stories file corresponding with 1939 reveals a short shorty titled "World Beneath Ice." Searching for the title on the internet does not immediately yield the story itself, corroborating a point made in the introduction, that Amazing Stories represents not only popular writers, but common people writing stories for their own enjoyment or for others' validation. The influence of historical events on common people is seemingly reflected in narrative.

"World Beneath Ice" contains a notable quote regarding the freezing of cells:

"If you knew much of science, you would realize that the quick-freezing of any animal or vegetable substance does not result in the cell-expansion and rupture that occurs in slow-freezing. Therefore, in an instantaneous freeze, there is no damage — just a complete suspension of activity. My daughter— all the peoples of Europe and Asia— are in a state, of suspended animatian, and if i were to allow the temperature to rise above freezing, slowly, carefully, almost all would revive . . ."

Its 1939 publication seemingly precedes research into cryopreservation, and is almost certainly inaccurate at the scales of entire human beings. An unfortunate drawback of the collected data is the notable lack of the term "microwave" anywhere, even though the application of microwave radiation to heat food was known since 1933. [4] This outcome demonstrates that the data-driven method is not foolproof, and there are considerable drawbacks to having little data.

It is worth mentioning that science fiction is often subject to authors with only superficial knowledge about a given subject, so certain concepts of science fiction stories may be conveyed at any level of accuracy, informed by the knowledge of the author, the popular knowledge of the subject, the tendency of public education to cover that subject, et cetera. Therefore it is advised to take great care with data-driven searches like this, since no script can discriminate a well-described concept from a poorly described concept.

The following cells exemplify one of the potential perils of data-driven methodology.

Yet again, the output appears promising. Investigating the large peaks in the Nature data reveals research done with regards to the velocity and the behaviour of light, probably spurred by quantum mechanics. However, certain issues in the terminology arise, since idioms like "new light" and "brought to light" as well as other definitions of the term, namely as the opposite of "heavy," skew the data. The issue is made much worse when investigating the Amazing Science data. While there are certainly intriguing datapoints, such as the publication of "The Colour out of Space" in 1927 by H. P. Lovecraft— whose entire premise hinges upon an impossible and corruptive colour of light— they pale in comparison to the commonplace and desirable usage of light to set the mood in a narrative.

Having technical and mathematical knowledge is only useful up to a certain point, since misconstruing certain commonalities as significances is much easier without an understanding of literature or narrative in general. Especially in an analysis of this kind, having an understanding of writing can better inform conclusions than the data alone. There are indeed cases in which the term "light" is used to refer to its speed in a vacuum, and occasionally in fascinating ways. One story, called "The Metal Horde," measures distance in light-seconds and incorporates the vastness of space in combination with the relatively slow speed of light to explain a failure in telecommunication. The majority, however, uses "light" to refer to brightness, and by extension as a way to control the description, be it following or limited by the light.

The output of S20 demonstrates the first instance of reduplication skewing the data in some way. The steep peak in 1936 is induced by a reduplication of the word "gravity" to appear four times due to an abstract on an "ultracentrifuge" appearing twice. There are four notable peaks in the Amazing Stories data, and though they do not neecssarily correlate with any Nature data, since there is little mention of "gravity" in the first place, they still merit some investigation.

The 1930 peak is the result of "The Metal Horde," in which accelerations and planets alike are described in terms of Earth's gravity to impart a sense of scale. The peak in 1938 is the result of various assertions made about gravity by various writers, but more notably that of a spacefaring story in which "gravity detectors" take on the role of letting a spaceship crew know there is a celestial body nearby. It should be obvious this does not correlate with scientific understanding, not even that of the time, since Albert Einstein had already published about general and special relativity before then. 13 The peak in 1941 points to various stories about machines that manipulate gravity in some way, either by reversing it or nullifying it completely. And 1944 points to a genuinely baffling story whose premise is that gravity is not a pulling force, but a pushing force.

Robots have been commonplace in science fiction since the very first use of the word in R.U.R. or Rossum's Universal Robots by Karel Čapek in 1920. [14] Amazing Stories displays a steady upwards trend in robotics-related concepts that seemingly drops off after 1943. That is not to say robotics suddenly vanished in science fiction afterwards, since the rival to Amazing Stories, Astounding Stories— a magazine whose title is equally creative— went on to publish the works of Isaac Asimov between the 1940s and 50s, which would later be compiled into the novel I, Robot. [15]

[14]: Original Czech language version: https://archive.org/details/rurrossumsuniver00apekuoft/page/n1/mode/2up

[15]: Internet Speculative Fiction Database listing: https://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/title.cgi?17201

By now, both the pros and cons of this methodology should be clear. Data-driven analysis is a powerful tool for digital history, and it can reveal a lot about a given subject. Provided the user has a broad enough and a deep enough dataset, they can see the influence of historical events among common people. The ideal case was given first to make a good impression. The influence the Manhattan Project had on fiction and research alike was widespread and powerful, from censorship of scientific ideas to FBI investigations spurred by science fiction that precedes science fact.

It is unfortunate that the available free archives of Astounding Stories are highly limited, since access to them may allow for a new dimension of data. Astounding Stories in the popular conception was a much more consistent publisher with a higher rate of publication. That does not discount Amazing Stories, however, for harbouring some of the greatest and most prolific science fiction writers in history. Upon investigating the plaintext files gathered by S1, the user can spot authors like H. G. Wells, H. P. Lovecraft, Jules Vernes, and more.

The first editor of Amazing Stories, Hugo Gernsback, is recorded to have said:

"Not only do these amazing tales make tremendously interesting reading— they are also always instructive. They supply knowledge that we might not otherwise obtain— and they supply it in a vert palatable form. For the best of these modern writers of scientifiction [sic] have the knack of imparting knowledge and even inspiration without once making us aware that we are being taught. [16]

Such a statement seems to have aged relatively well, considering the past analyses. The stories that he curated imparted knowledge well beyond their publication dates, likewise for Nature. Though not all the data was perfectly useful, and though not every concept could be mapped perfectly to some inspiration, the trends that did appear were certainly indicative of the time and place. As a methodology, this has potential.

[16]: The History of Science Fiction, Adam Roberts, p.176 (Science Library PN 3433.8 .R55 2006)

It is worth noting this data appears like a much rougher version of the Googe nGram viewer, which informed but a small part of the project at large. Performing similar searches to the ones performed in the preceding scripts may yield similar results, though backed by millions of books and near-infinite processing power. The technology already exists for large analysis. It need only be focused a little more tightly.
